revision.text:
'''Ahitub''' ({{Lang-he|אֲחִיטוּב}} ''’Ǎḥiṭūḇ'', "my brother is goodness") A few people in the Bible have this name:

(1.) The son of [[Hophni and Phinehas|Phinehas]], grandson of [[Eli (Judges)|Eli]], and brother of [[Ichabod]]. On the death of his grandfather Eli he most likely succeeded to the office of high priest, and would have been succeeded by his son [[Ahijah]] (references to Ahitub as the father of Ahijah are in 1 Sam. 14:3; 22:9, 11, 12, 20 and 1 Chr 9:11). [[Ahijah]] (also spelled Ahiah), who is listed as his son in [http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Samuel%2014:2-3,%2018-19;&version=9; 1 Samuel 14:2-3, 18-19], may have been the same person as [[Ahimelech]] ([http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Samuel%2022:9-20;&version=9; 1 Samuel 22:9-20]), or he may have been another son of Ahitub (probably an elder son if this was the case).

{{s-start}}
{{s-rel|isra}}
{{s-bef|before=[[Eli (Bible)|Eli]]}}
{{s-ttl|title=[[List of High Priests of Israel|High Priest of Israel]]}}
{{s-aft|after=[[Ahijah]]}}
{{s-end}}

(2.) The father of [[Zadok (High Priest)|Zadok]] ([http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=2%20Sam.%208:15-17;&version=9; 2 Sam. 8:15-17]). This Ahitub was the son of Amariah, Amarias or Arophaeus, who was the son of Meraioth, Meraoith or Merahoth, who was the son of Zerahiah or Zaraias, who was the son of [[Uzzi]], who was the son of [[Bukki]], who was the son of [[Abishua]], who was the son of [[Phinehas]], who was the son of [[Eleazar]], who was the son of [[Aaron]] ([http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Chronicles%206:3-8;&version=9; 1 Chronicles 6:3-8]). There is a faint possibility that this Ahitub was made high priest by [[Saul the King|Saul]] after the extermination of the family of [[Ahimelech]], but it is very unlikely as there are apparently no references supporting this. It is much more likely that Saul had no official high priest after this incident until the end of his reign (see Josephus's [http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=2359&pageno=193 Antiquities of the Jews, Book VI, Chapter XII, Paragraph 7].

(3.) A priestly descendant through the priestly line of the first [[Zadok (High Priest)|Zadok]]. This Ahitub is mentioned in [http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Chronicles%206:11-12;&version=9; 1 Chronicles 6:11-12]. To make matters a bit more confusing, this Ahitub also had a son (or probably grandson) by the name of Zadok. This Ahitub may have been high priest in the later time of the kings, but he also may not have been a high priest. He did become the ancestor of later high priests, which served during the fall of [[Jerusalem]] and post-exile.

(4.) An ancestor of a person mentioned in [http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?book_id=16&chapter=11&verse=11&version=9&context=verse Nehemiah 11:11]. This person might be one of the three aforementioned persons, but probably is not.

